# Cursor Plugins & Marketplace Guide

Plugins package rules, skills, agents, commands, MCP servers, and hooks into distributable bundles. They work across the IDE, CLI, and Cloud. Available since Cursor 2.5.

## What Plugins Contain

A plugin can bundle any combination of:

| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| Rules | Persistent AI guidance (`.mdc` files) |
| Skills | Specialized agent capabilities (`SKILL.md`) |
| Agents | Custom subagent configurations |
| Commands | Agent-executable command files |
| MCP Servers | Model Context Protocol integrations (`.mcp.json`) |
| Hooks | Automation scripts triggered by events (`hooks.json`) |

## Installing Plugins

Install from the [Cursor Marketplace](https://cursor.com/marketplace) or in-editor:
- Use `/add-plugin` in Agent chat
- Browse Cursor Settings > Plugins

Manage installed components:
- **MCP servers**: Toggle on/off in Cursor Settings > Features > Model Context Protocol
- **Rules/Skills**: Manage in Cursor Settings > Rules section. Toggle between Always, Agent Decides, and Manual modes.

## Plugin Structure

```
my-plugin/
├── .cursor-plugin/
│   └── plugin.json        # Required: plugin manifest
├── rules/                 # Auto-discovered .mdc/.md files
├── skills/                # Auto-discovered SKILL.md dirs
│   └── my-skill/
│       └── SKILL.md
├── agents/                # Auto-discovered .md files
├── commands/              # Auto-discovered .md/.txt files
├── hooks/
│   └── hooks.json         # Hook definitions
├── .mcp.json              # MCP server definitions
├── scripts/               # Hook and utility scripts
├── assets/
│   └── logo.svg           # Plugin logo
└── README.md
```

## Plugin Manifest (`plugin.json`)

Every plugin requires `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json`:

```json
{
  "name": "my-plugin",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "Brief plugin description",
  "author": {
    "name": "Your Name",
    "email": "optional@email.com"
  },
  "keywords": ["category", "tags"],
  "logo": "assets/logo.svg",
  "license": "MIT"
}
```

**Required**: Only `name` (lowercase, kebab-case, alphanumerics + hyphens + periods).

**Optional**: `description`, `version`, `author`, `homepage`, `repository`, `license`, `keywords`, `logo`, `rules`, `agents`, `skills`, `commands`, `hooks`, `mcpServers`.

## Component Discovery

When manifest does not specify explicit paths, automatic folder-based discovery applies:

| Component | Default Location | Discovery Method |
|-----------|-----------------|-----------------|
| Skills | `skills/` | Subdirectory containing `SKILL.md` |
| Rules | `rules/` | All `.md`, `.mdc`, `.markdown` files |
| Agents | `agents/` | All `.md`, `.mdc`, `.markdown` files |
| Commands | `commands/` | All `.md`, `.mdc`, `.markdown`, `.txt` files |
| Hooks | `hooks/hooks.json` | Parsed for hook event names |
| MCP | `.mcp.json` | Parsed for server entries |
| Root Skill | `SKILL.md` at root | Single-skill plugin (only if no `skills/` dir) |

Specifying a manifest field (e.g., `"skills": "./my-skills/"`) replaces folder discovery for that component.

## Multi-Plugin Repositories

A single Git repo can host multiple plugins via `.cursor-plugin/marketplace.json` at the repo root:

```json
{
  "name": "my-marketplace",
  "owner": { "name": "Org Name" },
  "metadata": { "description": "Plugin collection" },
  "plugins": [
    {
      "name": "plugin-one",
      "source": "plugin-one",
      "description": "First plugin"
    },
    {
      "name": "plugin-two",
      "source": "plugin-two",
      "description": "Second plugin"
    }
  ]
}
```

Each plugin directory uses its own `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json`. Marketplace entry values merge with per-plugin manifest (manifest takes precedence).

**Max 500 plugins per marketplace manifest.**

## Publishing

1. Create plugin following the structure above
2. Host in a public Git repository
3. Submit at [cursor.com/marketplace/publish](https://cursor.com/marketplace/publish)

**Submission checklist**:
- Valid `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json` manifest
- Plugin tested locally
- All paths relative (no `..`, no absolute paths)
- README documents usage and configuration
- All rules, skills, agents, commands have proper frontmatter
- `name` is unique, lowercase, kebab-case

**Coming soon**: Private team marketplaces for internal org distribution.

## Plugin Template

Use the [plugin template](https://github.com/cursor/plugin-template) to bootstrap new plugins. Includes two starters:
- `starter-simple`: Rules and skills only
- `starter-advanced`: Rules, skills, agents, commands, hooks, MCP, and scripts

Run `node scripts/validate-template.mjs` to validate before submission.

## Governance

Treat plugins like open source. License, security, and reliability checks still apply.

**Before installing or publishing:**
- **License**: Check plugin license; ensure compatibility with your use case
- **Security**: Review what the plugin runs (hooks, MCP servers, scripts). Plugins can execute code
- **Reliability**: Prefer plugins with clear maintenance, versioning, and documentation

**For teams:** Establish consensus on which plugins are approved. Unvetted plugins in shared environments introduce risk. See `cursor-security-guide.mdc` for MCP trust and auto-run considerations.

